A Jenkins CI/CD pipeline for a modern Java application works as an automated "assembly line."
It integrates various tools to ensure that every code change is built, tested, scanned for quality/security, and safely deployed.
Below is the standard flow, often defined in a Jenkinsfile (Pipeline as Code).

1. Source Code Integration (Checkout)
        The pipeline starts when a developer pushes code to a repository (like GitHub or Bitbucket). 
        Jenkins uses a Webhook to trigger the build.
        Action: Jenkins pulls the latest code from the specific branch.

2. Build & Unit Testing (JUnit)
    Jenkins uses a build tool (Maven or Gradle) to compile the Java code and run unit tests.
    Tool: JUnit.
    Pipeline Stage:
            Groovy
            stage('Build & Unit Test') {
                sh 'mvn clean test' // Runs JUnit tests automatically
            }
    Result: If any test fails, the pipeline stops immediately, and the developer is notified.

3. Static Code Analysis (SonarQube)
    Once the code compiles, Jenkins sends the source code and test results to SonarQube to check for "Code Smells," bugs, and technical debt.
    Tool: SonarScanner.
    Integration: Uses the withSonarQubeEnv wrapper to handle credentials.
    Quality Gate: You can configure the pipeline to fail if the SonarQube "Quality Gate" (e.g., less than 80% coverage) isn't met.

4. Static Application Security Testing (Checkmarx)
    Checkmarx (SAST) scans the source code specifically for security vulnerabilities (like SQL injection or hardcoded secrets) before the application is even running.
    Integration: Installed via the Checkmarx Jenkins plugin.
    Action: It zips the source code, sends it to the Checkmarx server, and waits for a security report.

5. Integration Testing (IT Cases)
    Unlike unit tests, Integration Tests verify that your microservice correctly interacts with databases, caches (like Redis), or other services.
    Tool: Maven Failsafe plugin or Testcontainers.
    Action: Jenkins might spin up a temporary Docker container (using Docker-in-Docker) to run these tests in a realistic environment.

6. Security Vulnerability Scan (SCA)
    While Checkmarx looks at your code, you also need to check your dependencies (the libraries in your pom.xml).
    Tools: Checkmarx SCA or Snyk.
    Goal: To find if you are using an old version of a library (like Log4j) that has a known vulnerability (CVE).

7. Deployment to Server (AKS/App Service)
    Once the "Artifact" (JAR/WAR file or Docker Image) is deemed safe, Jenkins deploys it.
    For AKS: Jenkins builds a Docker image, pushes it to Azure Container Registry (ACR), and then updates the Kubernetes manifest using kubectl or Helm.
    Stage Example:
        Groovy
        stage('Deploy to AKS') {
            sh 'helm upgrade --install my-app ./charts/my-app'
        }
8. Post-Deployment: DAST & Monitoring
        After the app is running on the server, you perform Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST).
        Tool: OWASP ZAP.
        Action: This "attacks" the running URL of your application to find vulnerabilities that only appear at runtime (
            like broken authentication or misconfigured headers).

Stage                Tool                Purpose
Code                Git / Java            The source of truth.
Unit Test            JUnit                Checks logic at the function level.
Quality            SonarQube              Checks code health and standards.
Security (Static)   Checkmarx             Scans source code for security flaws.
Security (Deps)    SCA (Checkmarx/Snyk)    Checks for vulnerable third-party libraries.
Integration        IT / Docker            Checks how parts work together.
Deploy              AKS / Helm            Pushes the app to the live environment.
Security (Dynamic)    OWASP ZAP            Scans the running app for vulnerabilities.

